- **Backend:** <e.g. FastAPI + SQLModel + Postgres>. Why → `L01`.
- **Frontend:** <e.g. React + TypeScript, or "none — API only">. Why → `Lxx`.
- **Other:** <queue / cache / AI / payments as they're chosen>.

## Code values

- Explicit types at every boundary (request/response, external calls, stored
  shapes). No implicit `Any` / `dict[str, Any]` / untyped escape hatch.
- Self-documenting code. Names carry meaning. Comment only where the *why* isn't
  obvious (a hidden constraint, a bug workaround) — never to restate the code.
- One operation per routine, one concern per class, one concern per file. A file
  that grows to mix concerns = a boundary problem → surface it, don't bury it.
- Information hiding: each module hides one design secret — a likely-change area,
  an external format, a complexity source. Ask "what does this hide?", not "what's
  convenient to expose?". Vendor/external types stop at their client boundary.
- Simplest thing that works. Three similar lines beat a premature abstraction. No
  speculative features, no flexibility nobody asked for.
- Build exactly to the spec — every acceptance criterion met, nothing extra. Scope
  changes go back to the human, not into the diff.
- Limits/caps live in code (env var + check), not just infra.

## Coupling

Goal: simpler and more maintainable over time. Hidden cross-module coupling = a
silent bug factory.

- Each module/app owns its data — single writer. No second writer to the same
  store.
- Cross-module reads via a typed contract: an event, a read-only view, or the
  owner's typed client. Never reach into another module's internals.
- Shared code = error classes, base models, cross-cutting enums, transport/auth
  helpers. NOT domain logic.
- No singletons, no mutable globals. Dependencies injected at startup (framework
  DI / task context); tests inject fakes.

Reason: a change in one module must not silently break its readers. Typed contract
at every cross-module edge.

## File + function boundaries

No fixed line counts — they invite gaming. Surface a boundary problem to the human
when:

- A function can't be named in one sentence → mixed responsibilities.
- A file mixes concerns (e.g. transport + persistence + business rule together).
- A change needs editing 3+ unrelated places → coupling problem.
- A param list passes ~5 raw args → group into a typed object.
- Nesting passes ~3 deep → extract guard clauses / early returns.
- A function both decides and acts → split "decide" from "do".

## Validation + assertions

Types are the primary contract. Validate at the boundary, then trust the types
inside — no repeated re-validation.

- Inbound boundary: typed request models reject malformed input automatically.
- Storage: schema constraints (NOT NULL, FK, CHECK) enforce shape.
- External responses: parsed into your own types at the client edge.

Assertions + early returns for what types can't express: cross-system invariants
("row must be state X before Y"), guard clauses that fail fast on disallowed
combinations, dev-time impossible-bug detection.

Naming: positive boolean predicates (`is_paid`, `has_stock`); negated forms
(`not_unpaid`) banned.

## Naming

- English throughout: identifiers, files, comments, commits, PR titles.
- Domain-language terms (local language, transliterations) only in user-facing
  strings → a translations layer. Map external/legacy names to English at the
  boundary, not in the core.

## State management

State = what survives a crash and decides the next action. Treat it accordingly.

- One single source of truth (typically the primary DB). One place to look,
  migrate, audit. Two stores for the same fact = drift.
- Ephemeral op state (session ids, lease holders, tokens) = nullable columns on
  the existing row, so one row tells the full story — not a side store with a TTL.
- Cache/broker (e.g. Redis) is transient, never the source of truth. Crash + wipe
  → rebuild from the SoT.
- In-memory holds only non-serializable handles (task objects, file descriptors);
  a restart drops them by design.
- Data-shape classes stay shape-only. Business operations (state transitions,
  rules, side effects) live in modules, not as methods on the table class.

## Failure handling

Two tiers; path criticality decides the response.

- **Critical paths** (money, identity — payments, orders, login/session, account
  writes): fail loud. Raise and surface. No silent retry, no fallback. A hidden
  failure here compounds and costs trust.
- **Non-critical paths** (background pipelines — sync, reindex, mirrors,
  notifications): bounded retry + backoff (configured N attempts + max delay).
  Retries exhausted → log + alarm, exit the task. No infinite loop, no zombie
  process. A state machine on a row tracks attempts + last error; a reconciliation
  job picks up dead work.

## External service clients

Each external service gets its own client. The app calls the client; the client
calls the API. The app never imports a vendor SDK directly.

- One client per vendor (`clients/<vendor>/`). It owns transport, auth,
  retry/timeout, response→typed mapping, and log redaction.
- The client returns your own types; vendor SDK objects never escape it.
- Tests mock the client interface, not the SDK. Swapping a vendor = rewriting one
  client file, callers untouched.

## Migrations + deploy safety

Default = forward-compatible / zero-downtime: old code keeps working as new code
rolls out (add nullable column, add index, add table, add enum value).

Requires a window + plan + explicit approval: rename, drop, `NOT NULL` on a
populated column, type change, FK on a large table. Every migration carries a
safety note (zero-downtime, or requires-window + reason + rollback procedure).

## Testing

Pyramid, with critical paths always covered.

- **Unit** — fast, pure logic + branching, local feedback.
- **Integration** — real datastore/dependencies at module boundaries.
- **Critical-path e2e** — mandatory for money/identity flows, no mocks on the
  critical hops.
- Tests verify behavior from the user's perspective. Asserting internal call
  counts / private methods is banned.

## Logging + sensitive data

Structured logger from day one. Tiered redaction.

- Plain typed fields for correlation (ids, status, attempt, trace id).
- Redact by default: raw payloads, request/response bodies, prompts, free-form
  blobs. Hash for correlation when needed; an explicit grep-able flag to override.
- Every decision branch and error path logs enough context to reproduce.
- No PII in URLs (phones/emails as query params) — banned.

## Tech debt + refactoring

- Refactor for taste = no. Refactor when a boundary breaks (a file no longer maps
  to one concern, or a feature needs touching N unrelated files) = yes, as its own
  scoped task surfaced to the human.
- Debt found during normal work → a `docs/tech_debt/active/` item (location +
  smell + suggested fix). No silent fix in an unrelated change.
- "Good enough for MVP" / "not my responsibility" is not a reason to drop error
  handling, edge cases, or validation the spec implies. A deliberate cut is a
  logged tech_debt item with a trigger and the owner's sign-off, never silent.

## Operational baseline

Ships with the initial implementation, not as a follow-up.

- Tests per the pyramid; critical paths covered.
- Structured logs at decision branches + errors, with redaction.
- Error handling + rollback on every DB / external call — a failure leaves no
  half-write.
- Type checker + linter pass at commit (pre-commit owns this).
- No fake-done: no `TODO` / `pass` / `NotImplementedError` / hardcoded happy-path
  / mock-as-real shipped as complete.

## Dependencies

- Latest compatible versions; avoid stale pins. Commit the lockfile.
- Pre-commit owns format/lint — skip manual runs.
- A new dependency = ask first. Each is a long-term commitment; prefer the stdlib
  or an already-present library for what a few lines can do.

